\
\'93What\'92ll we do with ourselves this afternoon?\'94 cried Daisy, \'93and the\
day after that, and the next thirty years?\'94\
\
\'93Don\'92t be morbid,\'94 Jordan said. \'93Life starts all over again when it\
gets crisp in the fall.\'94\
\
\'93But it\'92s so hot,\'94 insisted Daisy, on the verge of tears, \'93and\
everything\'92s so confused. Let\'92s all go to town!\'94\
\
Her voice struggled on through the heat, beating against it, moulding\
its senselessness into forms.\
\
\'93I\'92ve heard of making a garage out of a stable,\'94 Tom was saying to\
Gatsby, \'93but I\'92m the first man who ever made a stable out of a\
garage.\'94\
\
\'93Who wants to go to town?\'94 demanded Daisy insistently. Gatsby\'92s eyes\
floated toward her. \'93Ah,\'94 she cried, \'93you look so cool.\'94\
\
Their eyes met, and they stared together at each other, alone in\
space. With an effort she glanced down at the table.\
\
\'93You always look so cool,\'94 she repeated.\
\
She had told him that she loved him, and Tom Buchanan saw. He was\
astounded. His mouth opened a little, and he looked at Gatsby, and\
then back at Daisy as if he had just recognized her as someone he knew\
a long time ago.\
\
\'93You resemble the advertisement of the man,\'94 she went on innocently.\
\'93You know the advertisement of the man\'97\'94\
\
\'93All right,\'94 broke in Tom quickly, \'93I\'92m perfectly willing to go to\
town. Come on\'97we\'92re all going to town.\'94\
\
He got up, his eyes still flashing between Gatsby and his wife. No one\
moved.\
\
\'93Come on!\'94 His temper cracked a little. \'93What\'92s the matter, anyhow?\
If we\'92re going to town, let\'92s start.\'94\
\
His hand, trembling with his effort at self-control, bore to his lips\
the last of his glass of ale. Daisy\'92s voice got us to our feet and out\
