his mind, but not before Tom wheeled and faced him expectantly.\
\
\'93Have you got your stables here?\'94 asked Gatsby with an effort.\
\
\'93About a quarter of a mile down the road.\'94\
\
\'93Oh.\'94\
\
A pause.\
\
\'93I don\'92t see the idea of going to town,\'94 broke out Tom savagely.\
\'93Women get these notions in their heads\'97\'94\
\
\'93Shall we take anything to drink?\'94 called Daisy from an upper window.\
\
\'93I\'92ll get some whisky,\'94 answered Tom. He went inside.\
\
Gatsby turned to me rigidly:\
\
\'93I can\'92t say anything in his house, old sport.\'94\
\
\'93She\'92s got an indiscreet voice,\'94 I remarked. \'93It\'92s full of\'97\'94 I\
hesitated.\
\
\'93Her voice is full of money,\'94 he said suddenly.\
\
That was it. I\'92d never understood before. It was full of money\'97that\
was the inexhaustible charm that rose and fell in it, the jingle of\
it, the cymbals\'92 song of it \'85 High in a white palace the king\'92s\
daughter, the golden girl \'85\
\
Tom came out of the house wrapping a quart bottle in a towel, followed\
by Daisy and Jordan wearing small tight hats of metallic cloth and\
carrying light capes over their arms.\
\
\'93Shall we all go in my car?\'94 suggested Gatsby. He felt the hot, green\
leather of the seat. \'93I ought to have left it in the shade.\'94\
\
\'93Is it standard shift?\'94 demanded Tom.\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93Well, you take my coup\'e9 and let me drive your car to town.\'94\
\
The suggestion was distasteful to Gatsby.\
\
\'93I don\'92t think there\'92s much gas,\'94 he objected.\
\
\'93Plenty of gas,\'94 said Tom boisterously. He looked at the gauge. \'93And\
if it runs out I can stop at a drugstore. You can buy anything at a\
