\
\'93Come on, Daisy,\'94 said Tom, pressing her with his hand toward Gatsby\'92s\
car. \'93I\'92ll take you in this circus wagon.\'94\
\
He opened the door, but she moved out from the circle of his arm.\
\
\'93You take Nick and Jordan. We\'92ll follow you in the coup\'e9.\'94\
\
She walked close to Gatsby, touching his coat with her hand. Jordan\
and Tom and I got into the front seat of Gatsby\'92s car, Tom pushed the\
unfamiliar gears tentatively, and we shot off into the oppressive\
heat, leaving them out of sight behind.\
\
\'93Did you see that?\'94 demanded Tom.\
\
\'93See what?\'94\
\
He looked at me keenly, realizing that Jordan and I must have known\
all along.\
\
\'93You think I\'92m pretty dumb, don\'92t you?\'94 he suggested. \'93Perhaps I am,\
but I have a\'97almost a second sight, sometimes, that tells me what to\
do. Maybe you don\'92t believe that, but science\'97\'94\
\
He paused. The immediate contingency overtook him, pulled him back\
from the edge of theoretical abyss.\
\
\'93I\'92ve made a small investigation of this fellow,\'94 he continued. \'93I\
could have gone deeper if I\'92d known\'97\'94\
\
\'93Do you mean you\'92ve been to a medium?\'94 inquired Jordan humorously.\
\
\'93What?\'94 Confused, he stared at us as we laughed. \'93A medium?\'94\
\
\'93About Gatsby.\'94\
\
\'93About Gatsby! No, I haven\'92t. I said I\'92d been making a small\
investigation of his past.\'94\
\
\'93And you found he was an Oxford man,\'94 said Jordan helpfully.\
\
\'93An Oxford man!\'94 He was incredulous. \'93Like hell he is! He wears a pink\
suit.\'94\
\
\'93Nevertheless he\'92s an Oxford man.\'94\
\
\'93Oxford, New Mexico,\'94 snorted Tom contemptuously, \'93or something like\
that.\'94\
\
\'93Listen, Tom. If you\'92re such a snob, why did you invite him to lunch?\'94\
demanded Jordan crossly.\
\
\'93Daisy invited him; she knew him before we were married\'97God knows\
where!\'94\
\
We were all irritable now with the fading ale, and aware of it we\
drove for a while in silence. Then as Doctor T. J. Eckleburg\'92s faded\
eyes came into sight down the road, I remembered Gatsby\'92s caution\
about gasoline.\
\
\'93We\'92ve got enough to get us to town,\'94 said Tom.\
\
\'93But there\'92s a garage right here,\'94 objected Jordan. \'93I don\'92t want to\
get stalled in this baking heat.\'94\
\
Tom threw on both brakes impatiently, and we slid to an abrupt dusty\
stop under Wilson\'92s sign. After a moment the proprietor emerged from\
the interior of his establishment and gazed hollow-eyed at the car.\
\
\'93Let\'92s have some gas!\'94 cried Tom roughly. \'93What do you think we\
stopped for\'97to admire the view?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m sick,\'94 said Wilson without moving. \'93Been sick all day.\'94\
\
\'93What\'92s the matter?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92m all run down.\'94\
\
\'93Well, shall I help myself?\'94 Tom demanded. \'93You sounded well enough on\
the phone.\'94\
\
With an effort Wilson left the shade and support of the doorway and,\
breathing hard, unscrewed the cap of the tank. In the sunlight his\
face was green.\
\
\'93I didn\'92t mean to interrupt your lunch,\'94 he said. \'93But I need money\
pretty bad, and I was wondering what you were going to do with your\
old car.\'94\
\
\'93How do you like this one?\'94 inquired Tom. \'93I bought it last week.\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s a nice yellow one,\'94 said Wilson, as he strained at the handle.\
\
\'93Like to buy it?\'94\
\
\'93Big chance,\'94 Wilson smiled faintly. \'93No, but I could make some money\
on the other.\'94\
\
\'93What do you want money for, all of a sudden?\'94\
\
\'93I\'92ve been here too long. I want to get away. My wife and I want to go\
West.\'94\
\
\'93Your wife does,\'94 exclaimed Tom, startled.\
\
\'93She\'92s been talking about it for ten years.\'94 He rested for a moment\
against the pump, shading his eyes. \'93And now she\'92s going whether she\
wants to or not. I\'92m going to get her away.\'94\
\
The coup\'e9 flashed by us with a flurry of dust and the flash of a\
waving hand.\
\
\'93What do I owe you?\'94 demanded Tom harshly.\
\
\'93I just got wised up to something funny the last two days,\'94 remarked\
Wilson. \'93That\'92s why I want to get away. That\'92s why I been bothering\
you about the car.\'94\
\
\'93What do I owe you?\'94\
\
\'93Dollar twenty.\'94\
\
The relentless beating heat was beginning to confuse me and I had a\
bad moment there before I realized that so far his suspicions hadn\'92t\
alighted on Tom. He had discovered that Myrtle had some sort of life\
apart from him in another world, and the shock had made him physically\
sick. I stared at him and then at Tom, who had made a parallel\
discovery less than an hour before\'97and it occurred to me that there\
was no difference between men, in intelligence or race, so profound as\
the difference between the sick and the well. Wilson was so sick that\
he looked guilty, unforgivably guilty\'97as if he had just got some poor\
girl with child.\
\
\'93I\'92ll let you have that car,\'94 said Tom. \'93I\'92ll send it over tomorrow\
afternoon.\'94\
\
That locality was always vaguely disquieting, even in the broad glare\
of afternoon, and now I turned my head as though I had been warned of\
something behind. Over the ash-heaps the giant eyes of Doctor T. J.\
Eckleburg kept their vigil, but I perceived, after a moment, that\
other eyes were regarding us with peculiar intensity from less than\
twenty feet away.\
\
In one of the windows over the garage the curtains had been moved\
aside a little, and Myrtle Wilson was peering down at the car. So\
engrossed was she that she had no consciousness of being observed, and\
one emotion after another crept into her face like objects into a\
slowly developing picture. Her expression was curiously familiar\'97it\
was an expression I had often seen on women\'92s faces, but on Myrtle\
Wilson\'92s face it seemed purposeless and inexplicable until I realized\
that her eyes, wide with jealous terror, were fixed not on Tom, but on\
Jordan Baker, whom she took to be his wife.\
\
