\
There is no confusion like the confusion of a simple mind, and as we\
drove away Tom was feeling the hot whips of panic. His wife and his\
mistress, until an hour ago secure and inviolate, were slipping\
precipitately from his control. Instinct made him step on the\
accelerator with the double purpose of overtaking Daisy and leaving\
Wilson behind, and we sped along toward Astoria at fifty miles an\
hour, until, among the spidery girders of the elevated, we came in\
sight of the easygoing blue coup\'e9.\
\
\'93Those big movies around Fiftieth Street are cool,\'94 suggested\
Jordan. \'93I love New York on summer afternoons when everyone\'92s away.\
There\'92s something very sensuous about it\'97overripe, as if all sorts of\
funny fruits were going to fall into your hands.\'94\
\
The word \'93sensuous\'94 had the effect of further disquieting Tom, but\
before he could invent a protest the coup\'e9 came to a stop, and Daisy\
signalled us to draw up alongside.\
\
\'93Where are we going?\'94 she cried.\
\
\'93How about the movies?\'94\
\
\'93It\'92s so hot,\'94 she complained. \'93You go. We\'92ll ride around and meet you\
after.\'94 With an effort her wit rose faintly. \'93We\'92ll meet you on some\
corner. I\'92ll be the man smoking two cigarettes.\'94\
\
\'93We can\'92t argue about it here,\'94 Tom said impatiently, as a truck gave\
out a cursing whistle behind us. \'93You follow me to the south side of\
Central Park, in front of the Plaza.\'94\
\
Several times he turned his head and looked back for their car, and if\
the traffic delayed them he slowed up until they came into sight. I\
think he was afraid they would dart down a side-street and out of his\
life forever.\
\
But they didn\'92t. And we all took the less explicable step of engaging\
the parlour of a suite in the Plaza Hotel.\
\
The prolonged and tumultuous argument that ended by herding us into\
that room eludes me, though I have a sharp physical memory that, in\
the course of it, my underwear kept climbing like a damp snake around\
my legs and intermittent beads of sweat raced cool across my back.\
The notion originated with Daisy\'92s suggestion that we hire five\
bathrooms and take cold baths, and then assumed more tangible form as\
\'93a place to have a mint julep.\'94 Each of us said over and over that it\
was a \'93crazy idea\'94\'97we all talked at once to a baffled clerk and\
thought, or pretended to think, that we were being very funny \'85\
\
The room was large and stifling, and, though it was already four\
o\'92clock, opening the windows admitted only a gust of hot shrubbery\
from the Park. Daisy went to the mirror and stood with her back to us,\
fixing her hair.\
\
\'93It\'92s a swell suite,\'94 whispered Jordan respectfully, and everyone\
laughed.\
\
\'93Open another window,\'94 commanded Daisy, without turning around.\
\
\'93There aren\'92t any more.\'94\
\
\'93Well, we\'92d better telephone for an axe\'97\'94\
\
\'93The thing to do is to forget about the heat,\'94 said Tom impatiently.\
\'93You make it ten times worse by crabbing about it.\'94\
\
He unrolled the bottle of whisky from the towel and put it on the\
table.\
\
\'93Why not let her alone, old sport?\'94 remarked Gatsby. \'93You\'92re the one\
that wanted to come to town.\'94\
\
There was a moment of silence. The telephone book slipped from its\
nail and splashed to the floor, whereupon Jordan whispered, \'93Excuse\
me\'94\'97but this time no one laughed.\
\
\'93I\'92ll pick it up,\'94 I offered.\
\
\'93I\'92ve got it.\'94 Gatsby examined the parted string, muttered \'93Hum!\'94 in\
an interested way, and tossed the book on a chair.\
\
\'93That\'92s a great expression of yours, isn\'92t it?\'94 said Tom sharply.\
\
\'93What is?\'94\
\
\'93All this \'91old sport\'92 business. Where\'92d you pick that up?\'94\
\
\'93Now see here, Tom,\'94 said Daisy, turning around from the mirror, \'93if\
you\'92re going to make personal remarks I won\'92t stay here a minute.\
Call up and order some ice for the mint julep.\'94\
\
As Tom took up the receiver the compressed heat exploded into sound\
and we were listening to the portentous chords of Mendelssohn\'92s\
