The Buchanans\'92 house floated suddenly toward us through the dark\
rustling trees. Tom stopped beside the porch and looked up at the\
second floor, where two windows bloomed with light among the vines.\
\
\'93Daisy\'92s home,\'94 he said. As we got out of the car he glanced at me and\
frowned slightly.\
\
\'93I ought to have dropped you in West Egg, Nick. There\'92s nothing we can\
do tonight.\'94\
\
A change had come over him, and he spoke gravely, and with decision.\
As we walked across the moonlight gravel to the porch he disposed of\
the situation in a few brisk phrases.\
\
\'93I\'92ll telephone for a taxi to take you home, and while you\'92re waiting\
you and Jordan better go in the kitchen and have them get you some\
supper\'97if you want any.\'94 He opened the door. \'93Come in.\'94\
\
\'93No, thanks. But I\'92d be glad if you\'92d order me the taxi. I\'92ll wait\
outside.\'94\
\
Jordan put her hand on my arm.\
\
\'93Won\'92t you come in, Nick?\'94\
\
\'93No, thanks.\'94\
\
I was feeling a little sick and I wanted to be alone. But Jordan\
lingered for a moment more.\
\
\'93It\'92s only half-past nine,\'94 she said.\
\
I\'92d be damned if I\'92d go in; I\'92d had enough of all of them for one day,\
and suddenly that included Jordan too. She must have seen something of\
this in my expression, for she turned abruptly away and ran up the\
porch steps into the house. I sat down for a few minutes with my head\
in my hands, until I heard the phone taken up inside and the butler\'92s\
voice calling a taxi. Then I walked slowly down the drive away from\
the house, intending to wait by the gate.\
\
I hadn\'92t gone twenty yards when I heard my name and Gatsby stepped\
from between two bushes into the path. I must have felt pretty weird\
by that time, because I could think of nothing except the luminosity\
of his pink suit under the moon.\
\
\'93What are you doing?\'94 I inquired.\
\
\'93Just standing here, old sport.\'94\
\
Somehow, that seemed a despicable occupation. For all I knew he was\
going to rob the house in a moment; I wouldn\'92t have been surprised to\
see sinister faces, the faces of \'93Wolfshiem\'92s people,\'94 behind him in\
the dark shrubbery.\
\
\'93Did you see any trouble on the road?\'94 he asked after a minute.\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
He hesitated.\
\
\'93Was she killed?\'94\
\
\'93Yes.\'94\
\
\'93I thought so; I told Daisy I thought so. It\'92s better that the shock\
should all come at once. She stood it pretty well.\'94\
